  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How a B.Tech CSE can get a job at ISRO?",
  "response": "Getting a job at the Indian Space Research Organisation (ISRO) as a B.Tech Computer Science and Engineering (CSE) graduate is highly competitive but achievable with the right preparation and strategy. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide to help you:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Understand ISRO\u2019s Recruitment Process**\nISRO primarily recruits engineers through the **ISRO Centralized Recruitment Board (ICRB)**. The process involves:\n- **Written Test**: Objective-type questions on technical subjects, general aptitude, and reasoning.\n- **Interview**: Technical and HR interview rounds for shortlisted candidates.\n\nAlternatively, ISRO also recruits through:\n- **ISRO Apprenticeship Program** (entry-level positions)\n- **Direct Recruitment** (for experienced professionals)\n\n---\n\n### **2. Eligibility Criteria for B.Tech CSE**\nTo qualify for ISRO\u2019s recruitment:\n- **Educational Qualification**: B.Tech/B.E. in Computer Science or related field with a minimum of **65%** aggregate (or equivalent CGPA).\n- **Age Limit**: Generally, **21 to 35 years** (varies based on the job profile and relaxation for reserved categories).\n- **Nationality**: Indian citizenship.\n\n---\n\n### **3. Key Skills Required**\nISRO looks for candidates with strong technical and problem-solving skills. For B.Tech CSE graduates, focus on:\n- **Programming Languages**: C, C++, Java, Python\n- **Data Structures and Algorithms**\n- **Operating Systems**\n- **Database Management Systems (DBMS)**\n- **Computer Networks**\n- **Embedded Systems** (for space applications)\n- **Artificial Intelligence and Machine Learning** (optional but advantageous)\n- **Software Development** (web, mobile, or desktop applications)\n\n---\n\n### **4. Prepare for the Written Exam**\nThe ISRO exam for CSE includes:\n- **Technical Section**: Focus on core CSE subjects like programming, data structures, algorithms, OS, DBMS, and networks.\n- **General Aptitude**: Quantitative aptitude, logical reasoning, and English comprehension.\n- **Study Material**: Use standard textbooks like:\n  - C Programming by Dennis Ritchie\n  - Data Structures by Lipschutz\n  - Operating Systems by Galvin\n  - DBMS by Navathe\n- **Practice**: Solve previous years\u2019 ISRO papers and mock tests.\n\n---\n\n### **5. Gain Relevant Experience**\n- **Internships**: Apply for internships at ISRO or related organizations like DRDO, BARC, or NITI Aayog.\n- **Projects**: Work on projects related to space technology, embedded systems, or software development.\n- **Certifications**: Obtain certifications in relevant technologies (e.g., AI/ML, cloud computing, cybersecurity).\n\n---\n\n### **6. Stay Updated with ISRO Notifications**\n- Regularly check the official ISRO website (**www.isro.gov.in**) for job notifications and application deadlines.\n- Subscribe to job alert portals like **Sarkari Naukri** or **Rozgar Samachar**.\n\n---\n\n### **7. Networking and Guidance**\n- Connect with ISRO professionals on LinkedIn for insights and advice.\n- Join forums or communities related to space technology and engineering.\n- Consider attending ISRO outreach programs or seminars.\n\n---\n\n### **8. Alternative Pathways**\nIf direct recruitment is challenging:\n- Pursue **M.Tech in Aerospace, Embedded Systems, or CSE** to enhance your qualifications.\n- Apply for **ISRO\u2019s Research Fellowship Program** (e.g., JRF/SRF) if you\u2019re interested in research.\n- Work in related fields (e.g., DRDO, HAL, or private space companies like Agnikul or Skyroot) to build experience.\n\n---\n\n### **9. Be Persistent**\nISRO recruitment is highly competitive, so don\u2019t get discouraged by rejections. Keep improving your skills and applying consistently.\n\n---\n\nBy following these steps and staying dedicated, you can increase your chances of securing a job at ISRO as a B.Tech CSE graduate. Good luck! \ud83d\ude80",
  "temperature": 1.0,
